<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd">
<!-- We need a doctype to allow us to use special characters like &nbsp; 
	 We use a "strict" DTD to make IE follow the alignment rules. -->
	 
<html xmlns:t="http://tapestry.apache.org/schema/tapestry_5_4.xsd">
<body class="container">
	<h3>Validators</h3>
	Most input components can use Tapestry validators. Client-side and server-side, validation occurs AFTER translation.<br/><br/>
	
	Tapestry has these built-in validators: <em>Email</em>, <em>Max</em>, <em>MaxLength</em>, <em>Min</em>, <em>MinLength</em>, <em>None</em>, <em>Regexp</em>, and <em>Required</em>. 
	They all implement <a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/Validator.html">Validator</a>. <br/><br/>
	
	In this example the Textfields use <em>Required</em> and <em>MaxLength</em>.

	<div class="eg">
		<t:form class="form-horizontal" t:id="inputs">
			
			<div class="form-group">
				<t:label class="col-sm-3" for="firstName"/>
				<div class="col-sm-3">
					<t:textfield t:id="firstName" t:validate="required, maxlength=10" size="10"/>
				</div>
				<div class="col-sm-6">
					<p class="form-control-static">
						${firstName}
						&nbsp;&nbsp;
						<span class="text-muted">(required, maxLength=10)</span>
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="form-group">
				<t:label class="col-sm-3" for="lastName"/>
				<div class="col-sm-3">
					<t:textfield t:id="lastName" t:validate="required, maxlength=10" size="10"/>
				</div>
				<div class="col-sm-6">
					<p class="form-control-static">
						${lastName}
						&nbsp;&nbsp;
						<span class="text-muted">(required, maxLength=10)</span>
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="form-group">
				<div class="col-sm-3 col-sm-offset-3">
					<input class="btn btn-primary" type="submit" value="Display" />
				</div>
			</div>
			
		</t:form>
	</div>
	
	Validators can have a client-side implementation, usually written in JavaScript. Validators ALWAYS have a server-side implementation.<br/>
	If the user disables JavaScript, it's not a data risk - the server-side validation will still run.<br/>
	You can turn off client-side validation programatically with the <code>clientValidation</code> parameter of Form.<br/><br/>

	References: 
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/Validator.html">Validator</a>, 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/forms-and-validation.html">Forms and Validation</a>,
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/Form.html">Form</a>, 
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/TextField.html">TextField</a>, 
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/PasswordField.html">PasswordField</a>, 
	<a href="http://people.apache.org/~hlship/t5api/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/TextArea.html">TextArea</a>.
